<section xml:id="sec-intro-to-exponential-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Intro to Exponential Functions</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <example xml:id="ex-graph-2-x">
      <title>Graph of f(x) = 2^x</title>
      <p>
        Consider the graph of <m>f(x) = 2^x</m>. First, create a table of values, using <m>x</m>-values of <m>-2, -1, 0, 1</m>, and <m>2</m>, and plugging them into the equation.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\begin{array}{c|l} x \amp f(x) \\ \hline -2 \amp 2^{-2} = \frac{1}{4} = 0.25 \\[4pt] -1 \amp 2^{-1} = \frac{1}{2} = 0.5 \\[4pt] 0 \amp 2^0 = 1 \\ 1 \amp 2^1 = 2 \\ 2 \amp 2^2 = 4 \end{array}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Then, connect these points with a smooth curve. Here is a graph: <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/ckryy4hneu">Graph of <m>f(x)=2^x</m></url>. Observe the <m>y</m>-values of <m>0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 4</m>. Notice that each time <m>x</m> increases by 1, the value of <m>y</m> is multiplied by 2.
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[>=stealth, baseline=(T.base)]
          \node[inner sep=0pt] (T) {$
            \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.1}
            \begin{array}{c|c}
            x \amp f(x) \\
            \hline
            -2 \amp 0.25 \\
            -1 \amp 0.5 \\
            0 \amp 1 \\
            1 \amp 2 \\
            2 \amp 4
            \end{array}
            $};
            
            % row centers along the right edge (6 rows total: header + 5 data rows)
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\tA}{1.5/6}
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\tB}{2.5/6}
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\tC}{3.5/6}
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\tD}{4.5/6}
            \pgfmathsetmacro{\tE}{5.5/6}
            
            \coordinate (rA) at ($(T.north east)!\tA!(T.south east)$);
            \coordinate (rB) at ($(T.north east)!\tB!(T.south east)$);
            \coordinate (rC) at ($(T.north east)!\tC!(T.south east)$);
            \coordinate (rD) at ($(T.north east)!\tD!(T.south east)$);
            \coordinate (rE) at ($(T.north east)!\tE!(T.south east)$);
            
            \foreach \a/\b in {rA/rB,rB/rC,rC/rD,rD/rE}{
              \draw[->]
              (\a) to[out=0,in=0,looseness=1.5]
              node[midway,right]{$\times 2$}
              (\b);
            }
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </example>
      
      <example xml:id="ex-graph-3-x">
        <title>Graph of f(x) = 3^x</title>
        <p>
          Consider the graph of <m>f(x) = 3^x</m>. First, create a table of values,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\begin{array}{c|c} x \amp f(x) \\ \hline -2 \amp 3^{-2} = \frac{1}{9} \approx 0.11 \\[4pt] -1 \amp 3^{-1} = \frac{1}{3} \approx 0.33 \\[4pt] 0 \amp 3^0 = 1 \\ 1 \amp 3^1 = 3 \\ 2 \amp 3^2 = 9 \end{array}</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          Here is a graph: <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/1yzfw670rx">Graph of <m>f(x)=3^x</m></url>. Notice that it grows faster than <m>2^x</m>, because each time <m>x</m> increases by 1, <m>y</m> multiplies by 3 (instead of 2).
        </p>
      </example>
      
      <example xml:id="ex-graph-half-x">
        <title>Graph of f(x) = (1/2)^x</title>
        <p>
          Consider the graph of <m>f(x) = \brac{\frac{1}{2}}^x</m>. Creating a table of values,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\begin{array}{c|l} x \amp f(x) \\ \hline -2 \amp \brac{\frac{1}{2}}^{-2} = 4 \\ -1 \amp \brac{\frac{1}{2}}^{-1} = 2 \\ 0 \amp \brac{\frac{1}{2}}^0 = 1 \\ 1 \amp \brac{\frac{1}{2}}^1 = \frac{1}{2} = 0.5 \\ 2 \amp \brac{\frac{1}{2}}^2 = \frac{1}{4} = 0.25 \end{array}</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          Here is a graph: <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/liceudb2ol">Graph of <m>f(x)=\brac{\frac{1}{2}}^x</m></url>. Here, each time <m>x</m> increases by 1, <m>y</m> is multiplied by <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, which means it gets smaller.
        </p>
      </example>
      
      <example xml:id="ex-graph-three-fourths-x">
        <title>Graph of f(x) = (3/4)^x</title>
        <p>
          Consider the graph of <m>f(x) = \brac{\frac{3}{4}}^x</m>. Creating a table of values,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\begin{array}{c|l} x \amp f(x) \\ \hline -2 \amp \brac{\frac{3}{4}}^{-2} = \frac{16}{9} \approx 1.78 \\ -1 \amp \brac{\frac{3}{4}}^{-1} = \frac{4}{3} \approx 1.33 \\ 0 \amp \brac{\frac{3}{4}}^0 = 1 \\ 1 \amp \brac{\frac{3}{4}}^1 = \frac{3}{4} = 0.75 \\ 2 \amp \brac{\frac{3}{4}}^2 = \frac{9}{16} \approx 0.56 \end{array}</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          Here is a graph: <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/af8qc50vbe">Graph of <m>f(x)=\brac{\frac{3}{4}}^x</m></url>. This graph also decreases, but more slowly than <m>\brac{\frac{1}{2}}^x</m>.
        </p>
      </example>
      
      <example xml:id="ex-compare-four-functions">
        <title>Comparing Exponential Functions</title>
        <p>
          Here are all of the 4 functions from the previous examples, graphed together: <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/rgv9ryb5ig">4 Examples of Exponential Functions</url>.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>What is different about them?</li>
          <li>What is similar or the same?</li>
        </ul>
      </example>
      
      <p>
        In general, for a function like <m>f(x)=b^x</m>, each time <m>x</m> increases by 1, the output is <em>multiplied</em> by the base <m>b</m>.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>If <m>b \gt 1</m>, the <m>y</m>-values <em>increase</em>.</li>
        <li>If <m>b \lt 1</m>, the <m>y</m>-values <em>decrease</em>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Also,
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The <m>y</m>-intercept is always <m>(0,1)</m>, because when <m>x=0</m>, the <m>y</m>-value is <m>b^0 = 1</m>.</li>
        <li>There are no <m>x</m>-intercepts, because <m>b^x</m> is never equal to 0.</li>
        <li>The domain is all real numbers, because you can raise a base to any exponent you want, positive or negative.</li>
        <li>The range is all positive numbers, or <m>y \gt 0</m>, because raising a number <m>b</m> to the exponent <m>x</m> always gives a positive output (even if <m>x</m> is negative).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Also, notice that all of the functions <q>flatten out</q> around the <m>x</m>-axis. We call this a <em>horizontal asymptote</em>. So, the graph has a horizontal asymptote of the <m>x</m>-axis, or the line <m>y=0</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    
    <subsection xml:id="sub-exponential-functions">
      <title>Exponential Functions</title>
      <definition xml:id="def-exponential-function">
        <p>
          An <term>exponential function</term> with base <m>b</m> is the function given by,
          <md>
            <mrow>\boxed{f(x) = b^x}</mrow>
          </md>
          where <m>b \gt 0</m> and <m>b \neq 1</m>.
        </p>
      </definition>
      
      <example xml:id="ex-list-exponential">
        <title>Examples of Exponential Functions</title>
        <p>
          Some exponential functions include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><m>f(x) = 2^x</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x) = 5^x</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x) = 1.13^x</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x) = \brac{\frac{1}{2}}^x</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x) = 0.78^x</m></li>
        </ul>
      </example>
      
      <example xml:id="ex-non-examples-exponential">
        <title>Non-examples</title>
        <p>
          Some functions that are not exponential functions include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><m>f(x) = x^2</m> (<m>x</m> is not an exponent, this is a polynomial function)</li>
          <li><m>f(x) = (-2)^x</m> (the base <m>b</m> must be positive)</li>
          <li><m>f(x) = 1^x</m> (the base <m>b</m> cannot be <m>1</m>)</li>
          <li><m>f(x) = x^x</m> (the base is not a constant)</li>
          <li>
            <p>
              In particular, note that a power function, of the form <m>f(x) = x^n</m>, is not an exponential function.
              <ul>
                <li>With a power function, the base is the variable <m>x</m>, and the exponent is a constant <m>n</m>.</li>
                <li>For exponential functions, the base is a constant <m>b</m>, and the exponent is a variable <m>x</m>.</li>
              </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </example>
      
      <p>
        For the exponential function <m>f(x)=b^x</m>,
      </p>
      
      <ul>
        <li><m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,1)</m>.</li>
        <li>No <m>x</m>-intercepts.</li>
        <li>Horizontal asymptote is <m>y = 0</m>.</li>
        <li>Domain is all real numbers, or <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m>.</li>
        <li>Range is all positive real numbers, or <m>y \gt 0</m>, or <m>(0,\infty)</m>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Also,
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>If <m>b \gt 1</m>, then <m>f</m> is <em>increasing</em>.</li>
        <li>If <m>0 \lt b \lt 1</m>, then <m>f</m> is <em>decreasing</em>.</li>
      </ul>
      
      <image width="100%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[>=stealth]
          
          % -------------------- left: y = b^x, b&gt;1 --------------------
          \begin{scope}
          \def\b{1.7} % slower growth
          
          % axes (no tick marks)
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2.4,0) -- (2.4,0) node[right]{$x$};
          \draw[-&gt;] (0,-0.3) -- (0,3.5) node[above]{$y$};
          
          % curve (arrows on both ends)
          \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;,domain=-2:2,samples=120]
          plot (\x,{pow(\b,\x)});
          
          % point and labels
          \node[above right] at (0.9,3.2) {$y=b^x,\ b&gt;1$};
          \end{scope}
          
          % -------------------- right: y = b^x, 0&lt;b&lt;1 --------------------
          \begin{scope}[xshift=7.2cm]
          \def\b{0.6} % slower decay
          
          % axes (no tick marks)
          \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2.4,0) -- (2.4,0) node[right]{$x$};
          \draw[-&gt;] (0,-0.3) -- (0,3.5) node[above]{$y$};
          
          % curve (arrows on both ends)
          \draw[thick,&lt;-&gt;,domain=-2:2,samples=120]
          plot (\x,{pow(\b,\x)});
          
          % point and labels
          \node[above right] at (0.9,2) {$y=b^x,\ 0&lt;b&lt;1$};
          \end{scope}
          
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      
      <p>
        Some other notes:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The horizontal asymptote is only approached on one side, so you might call it a <q>half</q> horizontal asymptote.</li>
      </ul>
      
      <p>
        In summary,
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Create a table of values for <m>x = -2, -1, 0, 1, 2</m>, and plot the points.</li>
        <li>Connect the points with a smooth curve.</li>
      </ol>
    </subsection>
    
  </section>